VWe're at a tipping point in human history,
p4
aVa species poised between gaining the stars and losing the planet we call home.
p5
aa(lp6
VEven in just the past few years, we've greatly expanded
p7
aVour knowledge of how Earth fits within the context of our universe.
p8
aVNASA's Kepler mission has discovered
p9
aVthousands of potential planets around other stars,
p10
aVindicating that Earth is but one of billions of planets in our galaxy.
p11
aVKepler is a space telescope
p12
aVthat measures the subtle dimming of stars as planets pass in front of them,
p13
aVblocking just a little bit of that light from reaching us.
p14
aVKepler's data reveals planets' sizes
p15
aVas well as their distance from their parent star.
p16
aVTogether, this helps us understand whether these planets are small and rocky,
p17
aVlike the terrestrial planets in our own Solar System,
p18
aVand also how much light they receive from their parent sun.
p19
aVIn turn, this provides clues as to whether these planets that we discover
p20
aVmight be habitable or not.
p21
aa(lp22
VUnfortunately, at the same time as we're discovering this treasure trove
p23
aVof potentially habitable worlds,
p24
aVour own planet is sagging under the weight of humanity.
p25
aV2014 was the hottest year on record.
p26
aVGlaciers and sea ice that have been with us for millennia
p27
aVare now disappearing in a matter of decades.
p28
aVThese planetary-scale environmental  changes that we have set in motion
p29
aVare rapidly outpacing our ability to alter their course.
p30
aa(lp31
VBut I'm not a climate scientist, I'm an astronomer.
p32
aVI study planetary habitability as influenced by stars
p33
aVwith the hopes of finding the places in the universe
p34
aVwhere we might discover life beyond our own planet.
p35
aVYou could say that I look for choice alien real estate.
p36
aa(lp37
VNow, as somebody who is deeply embedded in the search for life in the universe,
p38
aVI can tell you that the more you look for planets like Earth,
p39
aVthe more you appreciate our own planet itself.
p40
aVEach one of these new worlds invites a comparison
p41
aVbetween the newly discovered planet and the planets we know best:
p42
aVthose of our own Solar System.
p43
aa(lp44
VConsider our neighbor, Mars.
p45
aVMars is small and rocky, and though it's a bit far from the Sun,
p46
aVit might be considered a potentially habitable world
p47
aVif found by a mission like Kepler.
p48
aVIndeed, it's possible that Mars was habitable in the past,
p49
aVand in part, this is why we study Mars so much.
p50
aVOur rovers, like Curiosity, crawl across its surface,
p51
aVscratching for clues as to the origins of life as we know it.
p52
aVOrbiters like the MAVEN mission sample the Martian atmosphere,
p53
aVtrying to understand how Mars might have lost its past habitability.
p54
aVPrivate spaceflight companies now offer not just a short trip to near space
p55
aVbut the tantalizing possibility of living our lives on Mars.
p56
aa(lp57
VBut though these Martian vistas
p58
aVresemble the deserts of our own home world,
p59
aVplaces that are tied in our imagination to ideas about pioneering and frontiers,
p60
aVcompared to Earth
p61
aVMars is a pretty terrible place to live.
p62
aVConsider the extent to which we have not colonized
p63
aVthe deserts of our own planet,
p64
aVplaces that are lush by comparison with Mars.
p65
aVEven in the driest, highest places on Earth,
p66
aVthe air is sweet and thick with oxygen
p67
aVexhaled from thousands of miles away by our rainforests.
