aa(lp96
VI leave you with a final thought experiment:
p97
aVFermi's paradox.
p98
aVMany years ago, the physicist Enrico Fermi asked that, given the fact
p99
aVthat our universe has been around for a very long time
p100
aVand we expect that there are many planets within it,
p101
aVwe should have found evidence for alien life by now.
p102
aVSo where are they?
p103
aVWell, one possible solution to Fermi's paradox
p104
aVis that, as civilizations become technologically advanced enough
p105
aVto consider living amongst the stars,
p106
aVthey lose sight of how important it is
p107
aVto safeguard the home worlds that fostered that advancement to begin with.
p108
aVIt is hubris to believe that interplanetary colonization alone
p109
aVwill save us from ourselves,
p110
aVbut planetary preservation and interplanetary exploration
p111
aVcan work together.
p112
aa(lp113
VIf we truly believe in our ability
p114
aVto bend the hostile environments of Mars for human habitation,
p115
aVthen we should be able to surmount the far easier task of preserving
p116
aVthe habitability of the Earth.
p117
